Akh'enet: City of the Eclipsed Ledger

Between the Southern Oasis and the pyramid approach roads stand the broken
walls of Akh'enet -- the legal-mortuary relay that bound oasis water law
to pyramid funerary authority. Caravans, bodies, debt, relics, and verdicts
all moved through this city on their way to deeper desert powers. Its oldest
creed survives in scratched stone: "What is unrecorded becomes famine."

The Bellwind Collapse

Tremor chains ruptured deep regulator shafts. Aquifer backflow carried brine
into civic cisterns. Resonance bells sounded without human hands. Archive
vaults flooded. The priestly courts called it judgment and doubled down on
descent rites. The Wardens demanded secular control. Akh'enet did not die;
it thinned, each district preserving a different political era in ruin.

Surviving Factions

The Reed Ledger Wardens maintain surviving gauges and witness-lamps: water
first, records second, ritual never above either. The Moon Sepulchrists
preserve descent rites; their militant wing seeks to reopen the Nadir
Palace. The Salt Jackal Reclaimers broker relics and forged seals across
desert markets. The Caravan Freeholds keep trade alive through neutral
hostels, remembering who can be paid and where water still rises.

The Districts

The Sunbreak March misdirects newcomers with bleached markers. The
Keeper Roadworks preserve pre-dynastic precision. The Shuttered Bazaar
is a contested gray market. The Cistern Veins echo with broken pressure
logic. The Necropolis Terraces carve judges as ferrymen and accountants
as priests. The Nadir Palace was built to reconcile court, water, and
death in one ceremonial machine -- its failure is Akh'enet's central myth.

Water, Death, and Silence

Water is testimony: every cistern draw is a legal claim. Death is
administrative continuity: contracts and debt survive the person, and tombs
include filing niches beside iconography. Silence is juridical technology:
moon-influenced courts clarified testimony through acoustic deprivation,
and a verdict issued from silence carried unmatched legitimacy.
